{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a0385631-27e9-470f-b203-8415a816d9a0","content":"Here's what you need for NativeAOT crash dump collection:\n\n**Environment variables** — since NativeAOT doesn't bundle `createdump`, you must point to it explicitly via `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpTool`:\n\n```yaml\n# Add to your container spec:\nenv:\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump\n    value: \"1\"\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType\n    value: \"4\"                          # 1=Mini, 2=Heap, 3=Triage, 4=Full\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName\n    value: \"/tmp/dumps/coredump.%p.%t\"\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpTool\n    value: \"/opt/tools/createdump\"\n\nsecurityContext:\n  capabilities:\n    add: [\"SYS_PTRACE\"]                 # required for createdump to attach\n\nvolumeMounts:\n  - name: crash-dumps\n    mountPath: /tmp/dumps\n\n# Add to your pod spec:\nvolumes:\n  - name: crash-dumps\n    emptyDir:\n      sizeLimit: 2Gi                    # adjust to your expected dump size\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`SYS_PTRACE`** is mandatory — `createdump` uses `ptrace` to read process memory.\n- **`DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpTool`** is required for NativeAOT since the runtime doesn't ship its own `createdump`.\n- **Type 4 (Full)** gives the most debuggable dumps; use **2 (Heap)** if storage is tight.\n- `emptyDir` is ephemeral — for persistence, swap it for a PVC or add a sidecar that ships dumps to blob storage.\n- The `%p` / `%t` tokens expand to PID and timestamp, preventing overwrites on repeated crashes.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ce517c00-3ba9-4f82-9ae1-993656158115","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to configure automatic crash dump collection for a NativeAOT .NET 11 app running in Kubernetes. They have `createdump` at `/opt/tools/createdump`. Let me think about what's needed:\n\n1. For .NET NativeAOT apps, crash dump collection works differently than regular CoreCLR apps. The environment variables needed are different.\n2. For NativeAOT in .NET 8+, the `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump` and related environment variables work with NativeAOT.\n\nLet me provide the environment variables and pod spec changes needed.\n\n\nI need to set up several environment variables to enable crash dump collection: enabling mini dumps, specifying the dump type as full, setting the output path to `/tmp/dumps/` with a pattern that includes process ID and timestamp, and pointing to the `createdump` tool at the specified location.\n\nFor NativeAOT specifically, I should note that the `createdump` tool isn't bundled with the runtime, so explicitly setting `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpTool` becomes essential to ensure the dumps are actually generated. For NativeAOT in .NET 7+, I need to set the environment variables for crash dump generation—`DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump`, `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType`, the dump file path, and point to the createdump tool. In Kubernetes, I'll also need to configure an emptyDir volume for storage, ensure the SYS_PTRACE capability is enabled so createdump can function, and mount the dumps directory in the pod spec.","outputTokens":1312,"requestId":"6408:1B0BB7:15F0F82:196DE02:69EC19DF"},"id":"5d990b28-71ee-4e97-a717-3628c2dfe5ae","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:33:42.685Z","parentId":"47298bce-a569-448c-b530-2500e1559482"}
